Exploratory Data Analysis of Loan default

In order to create a model for predicting loan defaults, we perform an initial data analysis on variables of our interest to see how they are correlated, followed by a detailed exploratory analysis of 15 selective variables (each commented with a reason for choosing the variable).

We further use variable selection methods like Stepwise Regression combined with Lasso regression to validate the significance of the variables chosen so we can come up with a Logistic model that contains the final set of variables which is a combination of both statistical as well as business significance. The accuracy of this Logistic model will be further verified by creating a Gains table at the end.

#Replace Negative with 0 for numeric columns 

cleanFun <- function(q){
  
  # set negative values as 0
  q[q < 0] <- 0
  
  # select numeric columns
  num_cols <- names(q)[sapply(q, is.numeric)]
  
  return (q[num_cols])
  
  }

df <- cleanFun(df)

cor(train$loan_default, train$AP001) #Age:
## [1] -0.02478795

## [1] -0.08483444

## [1] 0.0975438

## [1] 0.03856197
cor(train$loan_default, train$CR009) #Total loan amount
## [1] -0.02489878
cor(train$loan_default, train$CR017) #Debit card score_total
## [1] -0.04814849
cor(train$loan_default, train$CR018) #Debit card score_utility
## [1] -0.03425758
We observe that, of all the variables of our interest, Education (AP003) and Loan term (AP004) have the highest correlations, negative and positive, respectively with Loan default and we may expect these attributes to be part of our final model. Total loan amount (CR009) has the least correlation with loan default.

Exploratory Data Analysis of selective variables

#Function to compute the frequency of variable and store it in a dataframe

getfreq <- function(data, col_name){
  data %>%
    group_by_(col_name) %>%
    summarise(X_counts = n(),
              Y_counts = sum(loan_default)) %>%
    mutate(   Y_by_X_pcnt = Y_counts/X_counts,
              X_pcnt = X_counts/sum(X_counts))
}
#Function to generate one-way frequency bar chart

one_two_way_plot <-function(df1,var){
  
  theme_set(theme_bw())
  
  # Draw plot
  p1 <- ggplot(df1, aes(x=get(var), y=X_pcnt, fill=get(var))) + 
    geom_bar(stat="identity", width=0.8) + 
    labs(title="One-way frequency barchart", 
         subtitle=var, 
         caption="source: data") + 
    coord_cartesian(ylim=c(0,1)) +
    theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle=65, vjust=0.6))
  
  # Draw plot
  p2 <- ggplot(df1, aes(x=get(var), y=Y_by_X_pcnt, fill=get(var))) + 
    geom_bar(stat="identity", width=0.8) + 
    labs(title="% of Y by X", 
         subtitle=var, 
         caption="source: data") + 
    coord_cartesian(ylim=c(0,1)) +
    theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle=65, vjust=0.6))
  
  require(gridExtra)
  grid.arrange(p1, p2, nrow=2,heights=c(1, 1))
}

#Forward Stepwise variable selection
start_mod = lm(loan_default~1,data=train)
empty_mod = lm(loan_default~1,data=train)
full_mod = lm(loan_default~.,data=train)
forwardStepwise = step(start_mod,scope=list(upper=full_mod,lower=empty_mod),direction='forward')

Combining the results of Feature selection models of Forward, Backward and Hybrid Stepwise regression and Lasso regression, we perform Logistic regression on the 31 highly statistically significant variables as follows.

LOGISTIC REGRESSION

We use Logistic regression to create our final model as it is the most widespread technique, combining a high predictive capability with accuracy percentages not statistically significant, different from other more recent techniques
logismodel = glm(loan_default~AP003+AP004+MB005+CR015+PA023+AP002+CD113+PA029+TD001+AP008+CD117+TD005+AP006+CD170+TD010+CR018+CD137+CD132+CD008+CD152+CR017+TD013+CR017+CD106+CD107+AP007+TD009+TD014+CR004+PA022+PA028+CD123,data=train,family='binomial')

#Assess Performance on train sample
#Use predict function and construct classification table
pred = predict(logismodel,type='response')
ggplot(data=data.frame(pred),aes(x=pred))+
  geom_histogram(fill='steelblue3')
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

table(as.numeric(pred>0.5)) # how many predictions for loan default using a 0.5 cutoff
## 
##     0     1 
## 55171   829
ct = table(train$loan_default,pred>0.5);ct # classification table
##    
##     FALSE  TRUE
##   0 44695   406
##   1 10476   423
accuracy = sum(ct[1,1],ct[2,2])/nrow(train); accuracy
## [1] 0.8056786
We are interested in the Specificity which provides the ability to correctly identify the true defaulters of the lot
specificity = ct[1,1]/sum(ct[1,1],ct[1,2]); specificity
## [1] 0.990998
#How much better is the accuracy than just going with majority class
t = table(train$loan_default)
baseline = max(t[1],t[2])/nrow(train); baseline 
## [1] 0.805375
#Assess Performance (on test sample)
baseline = table(test$loan_default)[1]/nrow(test); baseline
##         0 
## 0.8087917
#compute prediction quality on the test sample using logismodel
pred_test = predict(logismodel,newdata=test,type='response')
ggplot(data=data.frame(pred_test),aes(x=pred_test))+
  geom_histogram(fill='steelblue3')
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

ct = table(test$loan_default,pred_test>0.5); ct
##    
##     FALSE  TRUE
##   0 19233   178
##   1  4422   167
accuracy = sum(ct[1,1],ct[2,2])/nrow(test); accuracy
## [1] 0.8083333
specificity = ct[1,1]/sum(ct[1,1],ct[1,2]); specificity
## [1] 0.9908299
The model’s accuracy on both Train and Test data is approximately equal to 80% which shows that there is neither overfitting nor underfitting happened with our model which is good.
ROCRpred = prediction(pred_test,test$loan_default)
as.numeric(performance(ROCRpred,"auc")@y.values) # auc measure
## [1] 0.7023915
test <- cbind(test, pred_test)

Gains Table

In the Gains table, Test data set is scored and sorted from high to low probability of default and put into equal segments
gain.table <- with(test, gains(actual=loan_default, predicted=pred_test, optimal=TRUE, percents=TRUE))

Construct ROC plot

ROCRperf = performance(ROCRpred,"tpr","fpr")
plot(ROCRperf,xlab="False Positive Rate",ylab="True Positive Rate") # basic plot with labeled axes

For a perfect classifier the ROC curve will go straight up the Y axis and then along the X axis. In our case, it is somewhere in between indicating that the model has an intermediate performance power

Conclusion

1. We proposed a regression logistic model to predict loan default as it is the most widespread technique, combining a high predictive capability with accuracy percentages not statistically significant, different from other more recent techniques
2. Education(AP003) and Loan Term (AP004) turned out to be the most predictive factors of default based on our initial exploratory data analysis as well as the multiple variable selection methods and lasso regression, but other additional siginificant factors were also added to improve the accuracy of the model. The accuracy of our final logistic model was approximately 80%
3. Though Accuracy is a good metric for balanced classes, we further evaluated the model using Gains table.The gains table being model-agnostic, it can be used to compare the power of different models
4. The Lift is the measure of effectiveness of our predictive model calculated as the ratio between the results obtained with and without our predictive model. Our current model has a Cumulative Lift of 2.09 which is a reasonably good index
5. As part of the supplemental assignment, even variables with more than 98% of NA values were also included as part of our anomaly detection since anomalies tend to be a very small percentage of the dataset and we may lose them by ignoring such variables. This inclusion resulted in some significant difference in the %Y by X values of these variables during the exploratory data analysis and provided additional insights on potential key drivers that need to be considered for prediciton of loan defaults.
